@Node "AXIS_GET" "TextureStudio.guide/AXIS_GET"
@Next "AXIS_SET"
@Toc "ARexx commands"

AXIS_GET
--------

@{i}Command@{ui}
     AXIS_GET

@{i}Parameters template@{ui}
     None.

@{i}Return template@{ui}
     X_ALIGNMENT,Y_ALIGNMENT,Z_ALIGNMENT,
     X_SIZE,Y_SIZE,Z_SIZE,
     X_POSITION,Y_POSITION,Z_POSITION

@{i}Description@{ui}
     This command returns the axis settings for the currently selected
     texture.

@{i}Parameters@{ui}
     None.

@{i}Returns@{ui}
    X_ALIGNMENT,Y_ALIGNMENT,Z_ALIGNMENT
          These variables contain the axis alignment as floating point
          numbers.

    X_SIZE,Y_SIZE,Z_SIZE
          These variables contain the axis size as floating point
          numbers.

    X_POSITION,Y_POSITION,Z_POSITION
          These variables contain the axis position as floating point
          numbers.

@{i}Errors@{ui}
     rc = 0 if the operation was successful.

     rc = 10 if the operation failed for any reason, rc2 will contain a
     string describing the problem.

@{i}Example@{ui}
     The following example gets the current axis settings and puts them
     in a stem called axis. The settings can then be accessed by
     `axis.x_alignment', `axis.y_alignment' ....

          AXIS_GET STEM 'axis.'

@{i}Known bugs@{ui}
     None.

     See @{"AXIS_SET" Link "AXIS_SET"}.


@EndNode

@Node "AXIS_SET" "TextureStudio.guide/AXIS_SET"
@Next "CLOSE"
@Prev "AXIS_GET"
@Toc "ARexx commands"

AXIS_SET
--------

@{i}Command@{ui}
     AXIS_SET

@{i}Parameters template@{ui}
     X_ALIGNMENT,Y_ALIGNMENT,Z_ALIGNMENT,
     X_SIZE,Y_SIZE,Z_SIZE,
     X_POSITION,Y_POSITION,Z_POSITION

@{i}Return template@{ui}
     None.

@{i}Description@{ui}
     This command sets the axis settings for the currently selected
     texture.

@{i}Parameters@{ui}
    X_ALIGNMENT,Y_ALIGNMENT,Z_ALIGNMENT
          These variables contain the axis alignment as floating point
          numbers.

    X_SIZE,Y_SIZE,Z_SIZE
          These variables contain the axis size as floating point
          numbers.

    X_POSITION,Y_POSITION,Z_POSITION
          These variables contain the axis position as floating point
          numbers.

@{i}Returns@{ui}
     Nothing.

@{i}Errors@{ui}
     rc = 0 if the operation was successful.

     rc = 10 if the operation failed for any reason, rc2 will contain a
     string describing the problem.

@{i}Example@{ui}
     The following example sets the axis alignment so that the z-axis
     is perpendicular to the surface of a vertical plane.

          AXIS_SET X_ALIGNMENT -90 Y_ALIGNMENT 0 Z_ALIGNMENT 0

@{i}Known bugs@{ui}
     None.

     See @{"AXIS_GET" Link "AXIS_GET"}.


@EndNode

@Node "CLOSE" "TextureStudio.guide/CLOSE"
@Next "COLOUR_GET"
@Prev "AXIS_SET"
@Toc "ARexx commands"

CLOSE
-----

@{i}Command@{ui}
     CLOSE

@{i}Parameters template@{ui}
     NAME,ALL/S

@{i}Return template@{ui}
     None.

@{i}Description@{ui}
     This commands closes one or all of the currently open texures.

     If no parameters are supplied, only the currently selected texture
     is closes.

@{i}Parameters@{ui}
    NAME
          NAME is the name of the texture to be closed. This can be
          shortened to the first few characters in the name.

          The NAME string is case insensitve.

    FLUSH/S
          If FLUSH is given, all currently open textures are closed.

@{i}Returns@{ui}
     Nothing.

@{i}Errors@{ui}
     rc = 0 if the operation was successful.

     rc = 10 if the operation failed for any reason, rc2 will contain a
     string describing the problem.

@{i}Example@{ui}
     The following example closes the currently selected texture.

          CLOSE

     The next example closes any textures beginning with `Rad', which
     could close `Radar', `RadCheks' ....

          CLOSE "Rad"

     The following example flushes out all existing textures.

          CLOSE ALL

@{i}Known bugs@{ui}
     None.


@EndNode

@Node "COLOUR_GET" "TextureStudio.guide/COLOUR_GET"
@Next "COLOUR_SET"
@Prev "CLOSE"
@Toc "ARexx commands"

COLOUR_GET
----------

@{i}Command@{ui}
     COLOUR_GET

@{i}Parameters template@{ui}
     COLOUR/A

@{i}Return template@{ui}
     R/N,G/N,B/N

@{i}Description@{ui}
     COLOUR_GET gets the red, green and blue values of the given colour.

@{i}Parameters@{ui}
    COLOUR/A
          This specifies which colour is to be returned. Valid strings
          are:

         BACKGROUND (shortest abbreviation: BACK)
         LIGHT (shortest abbreviation: LIGHT)
         OBJECTCOLOUR (shortest abbreviation: OBJECTCOL)
         OBJECTFILTER (shortest abbreviation: OBJECTFIL)
@{i}Returns@{ui}
    R/N,G/N,B/N
          These are the red, green and blue componets of the given
          COLOUR, the numbers are between 0 and 255.

@{i}Errors@{ui}
     rc = 0 if the operation was successful.

     rc = 10 if the operation failed for any reason, rc2 will contain a
     string describing the problem.

@{i}Example@{ui}
     The following is an example where the colour of the light source
     is returned in the `light.' stem.

          COLOUR_GET LIGHT STEM 'light.'

@{i}Known bugs@{ui}
     None.

     See @{"COLOUR_SET" Link "COLOUR_SET"}.

     See @{"Colours window" Link "Colours window"}.


@EndNode

@Node "COLOUR_SET" "TextureStudio.guide/COLOUR_SET"
@Next "FILE_JOIN"
@Prev "COLOUR_GET"
@Toc "ARexx commands"

COLOUR_SET
----------

@{i}Command@{ui}
     COLOUR_SET

@{i}Parameters template@{ui}
     COLOUR/A,R/N,G/N,B/N

@{i}Return template@{ui}
     None.

@{i}Description@{ui}
     This command sets the red, green and blue components of the given
     COLOUR.

@{i}Parameters@{ui}
    COLOUR/A
          This specifies which colour is to be altered. Valid strings
          are:

         BACKGROUND (shortest abbreviation: BACK)
         LIGHT (shortest abbreviation: LIGHT)
         OBJECTCOLOUR (shortest abbreviation: OBJECTCOL)
         OBJECTFILTER (shortest abbreviation: OBJECTFIL)
    R/N,G/N,B/N
          These are the red, green and blue componets for the given
          COLOUR, the numbers should be between 0 and 255.

@{i}Returns@{ui}
     Nothing.

@{i}Errors@{ui}
     rc = 0 if the operation was successful.

     rc = 10 if the operation failed for any reason, rc2 will contain a
     string describing the problem.

@{i}Example@{ui}
     The following example sets the colour of the background to be
     white.

          COLOUR_SET BACKGROUND 255 255 255

     The following example turns the red component of the light source
     off.

          COLOUR_SET LIGHT R 0

@{i}Known bugs@{ui}
     None.

     See @{"COLOUR_GET" Link "COLOUR_GET"}.

     See @{"Colours window" Link "Colours window"}.


@EndNode

@Node "FILE_JOIN" "TextureStudio.guide/FILE_JOIN"
@Next "FILE_SPLIT"
@Prev "COLOUR_SET"
@Toc "ARexx commands"

FILE_JOIN
---------

@{i}Command@{ui}
     FILE_JOIN

@{i}Parameters template@{ui}
     PATHPART/A, FILEPART/A

@{i}Return template@{ui}
     FILE

@{i}Description@{ui}
     Joins the path part of a filename to the file part of a filename,
     returning the full filename. Adds `/' and `:' where appropriate to
     create a full filename.

@{i}Parameters@{ui}
    PATHPART/A
          The path (directory) part of the filename to be created.

    FILEPART/A
          The file part of the filename to be created.

@{i}Returns@{ui}
    FILE
          The full filename created from the path and file parts.

@{i}Errors@{ui}
     rc = 0 if the operation was successful.

     rc = 10 if the operation failed for any reason, rc2 will contain a
     string describing the problem.

@{i}Example@{ui}
     The following creates the filename "Textures/Radar.itx" from the
     seperate path and fileparts - the result is put in a pop up
     requester:

          FILE_JOIN PATHPART "Textures" FILEPART "Radar.itx"
          
          REQUEST_MESSAGE TEXT '"'RESULT'"'

     The following creates the filename "Ram:Radar.itx" from the
     seperate path and fileparts (note how the '/' seperater is not
     needed) - the result is put in a pop up requester:

          FILE_JOIN PATHPART "Ram:" FILEPART "Radar.itx"
          
          REQUEST_MESSAGE TEXT '"'RESULT'"'

@{i}Known bugs@{ui}
     None.

     See @{"FILE_SPLIT" Link "FILE_SPLIT"}.


@EndNode

@Node "FILE_SPLIT" "TextureStudio.guide/FILE_SPLIT"
@Next "GUI_BLOCK"
@Prev "FILE_JOIN"
@Toc "ARexx commands"

FILE_SPLIT
----------

@{i}Command@{ui}
     FILE_SPLIT

@{i}Parameters template@{ui}
     FILE/A

@{i}Return template@{ui}
     PATHPART, FILEPART

@{i}Description@{ui}
     Splits the given filename into seperate path and file parts.

@{i}Parameters@{ui}
    FILE/A
          The full filename to be split.

@{i}Returns@{ui}
    PATHPART
          The path (directory) part of the filename.

    FILEPART
          The file part of the filename.

@{i}Errors@{ui}
     rc = 0 if the operation was successful.

     rc = 10 if the operation failed for any reason, rc2 will contain a
     string describing the problem.

@{i}Example@{ui}
     The following seperates the filename "Textures/Radar.itx" into
     seperate path and fileparts - the result is put in a pop up
     requester:

          FILE_SPLIT FILE "Textures/Radar.itx" STEM FILENAME.
          
          REQUEST_MESSAGE TEXT '"Path:'FILENAME.PATHPART,
             'File:'FILENAME.FILEPART'"'

     The following seperates the filename "Ram:Radar.itx" into seperate
     path and fileparts - the result is put into the default settings
     of a file requester:

          FILE_SPLIT FILE "Ram:Radar.itx" STEM FILENAME.
          
          REQUEST_FILE PATHPART '"'FILENAME.PATHPART'"',
             FILE '"'FILENAME.PATHPART'"'

@{i}Known bugs@{ui}
     None.

     See @{"FILE_JOIN" Link "FILE_JOIN"}.


@EndNode

@Node "GUI_BLOCK" "TextureStudio.guide/GUI_BLOCK"
@Next "GUI_UNBLOCK"
@Prev "FILE_SPLIT"
@Toc "ARexx commands"

GUI_BLOCK
---------

@{i}Command@{ui}
     GUI_BLOCK

@{i}Parameters template@{ui}
     None.

@{i}Return template@{ui}
     None.

@{i}Description@{ui}
     Blocks any input to all of TextureStudio's windows. Stops the user
     from altering anything whilst a script is running.

     Note: Always remember to unblock the GUI once you have finished
     the script.

@{i}Parameters@{ui}
     None.

@{i}Returns@{ui}
     Nothing.

@{i}Errors@{ui}
     rc = 0 if the operation was successful.

     rc = 10 if the operation failed for any reason, rc2 will contain a
     string describing the problem.

@{i}Example@{ui}
     The following example blocks input to all the windows.

          GUI_BLOCK

@{i}Known bugs@{ui}
     None.

     See @{"GUI_UNBLOCK" Link "GUI_UNBLOCK"}.


@EndNode

@Node "GUI_UNBLOCK" "TextureStudio.guide/GUI_UNBLOCK"
@Next "LIGHT_GET"
@Prev "GUI_BLOCK"
@Toc "ARexx commands"

GUI_UNBLOCK
-----------

@{i}Command@{ui}
     GUI_UNBLOCK

@{i}Parameters template@{ui}
     None.

@{i}Return template@{ui}
     None.

@{i}Description@{ui}
     Unblocks all the windows after a GUI_BLOCK call. Allows the user
     to interact with the program again.

     Note: it is safe to call GUI_UNBLOCK, even if the windows are not
     currently blocked by GUI_BLOCK.

@{i}Parameters@{ui}
     None.

@{i}Returns@{ui}
     Nothing.

@{i}Errors@{ui}
     rc = 0 if the operation was successful.

     rc = 10 if the operation failed for any reason, rc2 will contain a
     string describing the problem.

@{i}Example@{ui}
     The following unblocks all the windows.

          GUI_UNBLOCK

@{i}Known bugs@{ui}
     None.

     See @{"GUI_BLOCK" Link "GUI_BLOCK"}.


@EndNode

@Node "LIGHT_GET" "TextureStudio.guide/LIGHT_GET"
@Next "LIGHT_SET"
@Prev "GUI_UNBLOCK"
@Toc "ARexx commands"

LIGHT_GET
---------

@{i}Command@{ui}
     LIGHT_GET

@{i}Parameters template@{ui}
     None.

@{i}Return template@{ui}
     X_POS,Z_POS,INTENSITY/N,BACKLIGHT/N,POSITION,DISTANCE

@{i}Description@{ui}
     Gets the current settings about the light source.

@{i}Parameters@{ui}
     None.

@{i}Returns@{ui}
    X_POS,Z_POS
          These give the position of the light relative to the width of
          the scene visible. The floating point numbers are between -1
          and 1.

          -1 corresponds to the extreme left and bottom.   1
          corresponds to the extreme right and top.

    INTENSITY
          Gives the current light intensity from 0 to 200%.

    BACKLIGHT
          Gives the backlighting setting from 0 to 100%.

    POSITION
          This is a string containing the current setting of the
          `Position' slider in the light window. Can be `TOPLEFT',
          `TOP', `TOPRIGHT', `LEFT', `CENTRE', `RIGHT', `BOTTOMLEFT',
          `BOTTOM', `BOTTOMRIGHT' or `CUSTOM'.

    DISTANCE
          Gives the distance of the light source from the centre of the
          scene.

@{i}Errors@{ui}
     rc = 0 if the operation was successful.

     rc = 10 if the operation failed for any reason, rc2 will contain a
     string describing the problem.

@{i}Example@{ui}
     The following example gets the current light settings and puts
     them in a stem called `light.'.

          LIGHT_GET STEM 'light.'

@{i}Known bugs@{ui}
     None.

     See @{"LIGHT_SET" Link "LIGHT_SET"}.

     See @{"Light window" Link "Light window"}.


@EndNode

@Node "LIGHT_SET" "TextureStudio.guide/LIGHT_SET"
@Next "OBJECT_GET"
@Prev "LIGHT_GET"
@Toc "ARexx commands"

LIGHT_SET
---------

@{i}Command@{ui}
     LIGHT_SET

@{i}Parameters template@{ui}
     X_POS,Z_POS,INTENSITY/N,BACKLIGHT/N,POSITION,DISTANCE

@{i}Return template@{ui}
     None.

@{i}Description@{ui}
     Sets the current settings for the light source.

@{i}Parameters@{ui}
    X_POS,Z_POS
          These set the position of the light relative to the width of
          the scene visible. The floating point numbers must be between
          -1 and 1.

          -1 corresponds to the extreme left and bottom.   1
          corresponds to the extreme right and top.

    INTENSITY
          Sets the current light intensity from 0 to 200%.

    BACKLIGHT
          Sets the backlighting setting from 0 to 100%.

    POSITION
          This is a string containing the current setting of the
          `Position' slider in the light window. Must be `TOPLEFT',
          `TOP', `TOPRIGHT', `LEFT', `CENTRE', `RIGHT', `BOTTOMLEFT',
          `BOTTOM', `BOTTOMRIGHT' or `CUSTOM'.

    DISTANCE
          Sets the distance of the light source from the centre of the
          scene.

@{i}Returns@{ui}
     Nothing.

@{i}Errors@{ui}
     rc = 0 if the operation was successful.

     rc = 10 if the operation failed for any reason, rc2 will contain a
     string describing the problem.

@{i}Example@{ui}
     The following example sets the light source to be in the extreme
     top right position.

          LIGHT_SET X_POS 1 Z_POS 1 POSITION "CUSTOM"

@{i}Known bugs@{ui}
     None.

     See @{"LIGHT_GET" Link "LIGHT_GET"}.

     See @{"Light window" Link "Light window"}.


@EndNode

@Node "OBJECT_GET" "TextureStudio.guide/OBJECT_GET"
@Next "OBJECT_SET"
@Prev "LIGHT_SET"
@Toc "ARexx commands"

OBJECT_GET
----------

@{i}Command@{ui}
     OBJECT_GET

@{i}Parameters template@{ui}
     None.

@{i}Return template@{ui}
     OBJECT,RADIUS

@{i}Description@{ui}
     Gets the current object type and radius.

@{i}Parameters@{ui}
     None.

@{i}Returns@{ui}
    OBJECT
          Name of the type of object, can be `PLANE', `CYLINDER' or
          `SPHERE'.

    RADIUS
          A floating point number representing the radius of the object.

@{i}Errors@{ui}
     rc = 0 if the operation was successful.

     rc = 10 if the operation failed for any reason, rc2 will contain a
     string describing the problem.

@{i}Example@{ui}
     The following gets the current object settings and places them
     into a stem called `object.'.

          OBJECT_GET STEM 'object.'

@{i}Known bugs@{ui}
     None.

     See @{"OBJECT_SET" Link "OBJECT_SET"}.

     See @{"Object window" Link "Object window"}.


@EndNode

@Node "OBJECT_SET" "TextureStudio.guide/OBJECT_SET"
@Next "OPEN"
@Prev "OBJECT_GET"
@Toc "ARexx commands"

OBJECT_SET
----------

@{i}Command@{ui}
     OBJECT_SET

@{i}Parameters template@{ui}
     OBJECT,RADIUS

@{i}Return template@{ui}
     None.

@{i}Description@{ui}
     Sets the current object type and radius.

@{i}Parameters@{ui}
    OBJECT
          Name of the type of object, can be `PLANE', `CYLINDER' or
          `SPHERE'.

    RADIUS
          A floating point number representing the radius of the object.

@{i}Returns@{ui}
     Nothing.

@{i}Errors@{ui}
     rc = 0 if the operation was successful.

     rc = 10 if the operation failed for any reason, rc2 will contain a
     string describing the problem.

@{i}Example@{ui}
     The following sets the current object to be a sphere of radius 30
     units.

          OBJECT_SET "SPHERE" 30

@{i}Known bugs@{ui}
     None.

     See @{"OBJECT_GET" Link "OBJECT_GET"}.

     See @{"Object window" Link "Object window"}.


@EndNode

@Node "OPEN" "TextureStudio.guide/OPEN"
@Next "PARAMETER_GET"
@Prev "OBJECT_SET"
@Toc "ARexx commands"

OPEN
----

@{i}Command@{ui}
     OPEN

@{i}Parameters template@{ui}
     FILE/A,FLUSH/S

@{i}Return template@{ui}
     None.

@{i}Description@{ui}
     This command opens a standard Imagine3 texture module. See
     @{"Open texture" Link "Open texture"}.

@{i}Parameters@{ui}
    FILE/A
          This specifies the full filename of the texture module to be
          loaded.

    FLUSH/S
          This specifies whether any existing textures should be
          flushed out before loading in the specified file. Note that
          the `Flush textures on open' preference is ignored from
          ARexx, see @{"Flush textures on open" Link "Flush textures on open"}.

@{i}Returns@{ui}
     Nothing.

@{i}Errors@{ui}
     rc = 0 if the operation was successful.

     rc = 10 if the operation failed for any reason, rc2 will contain a
     string describing the problem.

@{i}Example@{ui}
     The following opens a texture module called `Radar.itx' from the
     `Textures' drawer and closes all other textures.

          OPEN "Textures/Radar.itx" FLUSH

     The following loads the `Target.itx' file from the user's current
     texture directory.

     TEXTUREPATH_GET VAR 'texture_path'

     FILE_JOIN '"'texture_path'"' '"'Target.itx'"' VAR 'texture_file'

     OPEN '"'texture_file'"'

@{i}Known bugs@{ui}
     None.


@EndNode

@Node "PARAMETER_GET" "TextureStudio.guide/PARAMETER_GET"
@Next "PARAMETER_SET"
@Prev "OPEN"
@Toc "ARexx commands"

PARAMETER_GET
-------------

@{i}Command@{ui}
     PARAMETER_GET

@{i}Parameters template@{ui}
     INDEX/N/A

@{i}Return template@{ui}
     VALUE,TEXT

@{i}Description@{ui}
     This command is used to get a parameter value (floating point
     number) and text field (name of parameter). It gets the parameters
     from the currently selected texture.

@{i}Parameters@{ui}
    INDEX/N/A
          This is the index number of the parameter and must be from 0
          to 15.

@{i}Returns@{ui}
    VALUE
          This is the floating point number associated with the given
          parameter INDEX.

    TEXT
          This is the text field of the parameter, e.g. `Colour Red'.

@{i}Errors@{ui}
     rc = 0 if the operation was successful.

     rc = 10 if the operation failed for any reason, rc2 will contain a
     string describing the problem.

@{i}Example@{ui}
     The following gets the fifth (number 4) parameter from the current
     texture and returns the value and text in a stem called `param.'.

          PARAMETER_GET 4 STEM 'param.'

     The following example adds 1 onto the first parameter.

          PARAMETER_GET 0 STEM 'param.'
          
          new_value = param.value + 1
          
          PARAMETER_SET 0 '"'new_value'"'

@{i}Known bugs@{ui}
     None.

     See @{"PARAMETER_SET" Link "PARAMETER_SET"}.

     See @{"Parameters window" Link "Parameters window"}.


@EndNode

@Node "PARAMETER_SET" "TextureStudio.guide/PARAMETER_SET"
@Next "PREFS_GET"
@Prev "PARAMETER_GET"
@Toc "ARexx commands"

PARAMETER_SET
-------------

@{i}Command@{ui}
     PARAMETER_SET

@{i}Parameters template@{ui}
     INDEX/N/A,VALUE/A

@{i}Return template@{ui}
     None.

@{i}Description@{ui}
     Sets the given parameter to a given value for the currently
     selected texture.

@{i}Parameters@{ui}
    INDEX/N/A
          This is the index number of the parameter and must be from 0
          to 15.

    VALUE/A
          This is a floating point number associated with the given
          parameter INDEX.

@{i}Returns@{ui}
     Nothing.

@{i}Errors@{ui}
     rc = 0 if the operation was successful.

     rc = 10 if the operation failed for any reason, rc2 will contain a
     string describing the problem.

@{i}Example@{ui}
     The following sets the last parameter (number 15) to be 0

          PARAMETER_SET 15 0

@{i}Known bugs@{ui}
     None.

     See @{"PARAMETER_GET" Link "PARAMETER_GET"}.

     See @{"Parameters window" Link "Parameters window"}.


@EndNode

@Node "PREFS_GET" "TextureStudio.guide/PREFS_GET"
@Next "PREFS_SET"
@Prev "PARAMETER_SET"
@Toc "ARexx commands"

PREFS_GET
---------

@{i}Command@{ui}
     PREFS_GET

@{i}Parameters template@{ui}
     None.

@{i}Return template@{ui}
     ALLOWTRANSOBJECT/N,CALCSURFNORMALS/N,FULLLIGHTCALCS/N,
     ANTIALIASING,FILEFORMAT,JPEG_QUALITY/N

@{i}Description@{ui}
     Gets the current preferences.

@{i}Parameters@{ui}
     None.

@{i}Returns@{ui}
    ALLOWTRANSOBJECT/N
          0 for off, 1 for on. See @{"Allow transparent object" Link "Allow transparent object"}.

    CALCSURFNORMALS/N
          0 for off, 1 for on. See @{"Calculate surface normals" Link "Calculate surface normals"}.

    FULLLIGHTCALCS/N
          0 for off, 1 for on. See @{"Full light calculations" Link "Full light calculations"}.

    ANTIALIASING
          The anti-aliasing mode, can be `NONE', `LOW', `MEDIUM',
          `HIGH' or `VERYHIGH'. See @{"Anti-aliasing" Link "Anti-aliasing"}.

    FILEFORMAT
          The current render file format. Can be `IFF-ILBM', `JPEG' or
          `TARGA'. See @{"Render file format" Link "Render file format"}.

    JPEG_QUALITY
          The quality of the JPEG output. See @{"JPEG options" Link "JPEG options"}.

@{i}Errors@{ui}
     rc = 0 if the operation was successful.

     rc = 10 if the operation failed for any reason, rc2 will contain a
     string describing the problem.

@{i}Example@{ui}
     The following returns the current preference settings and returns
     them in a stem called `pref.'.

          PREFS_GET STEM 'pref.'

@{i}Known bugs@{ui}
     None.

     See @{"PREFS_SET" Link "PREFS_SET"}.


@EndNode

@Node "PREFS_SET" "TextureStudio.guide/PREFS_SET"
@Next "ARexx_RENDER"
@Prev "PREFS_GET"
@Toc "ARexx commands"

PREFS_SET
---------

@{i}Command@{ui}
     PREFS_SET

@{i}Parameters template@{ui}
     ALLOWTRANSOBJECT/N,CALCSURFNORMALS/N,FULLLIGHTCALCS/N,
     ANTIALIASING,FILEFORMAT,JPEG_QUALITY/N

@{i}Return template@{ui}
     None.

@{i}Description@{ui}
     Sets any given preference(s).

@{i}Parameters@{ui}
    ALLOWTRANSOBJECT/N
          0 for off, 1 for on. See @{"Allow transparent object" Link "Allow transparent object"}.

    CALCSURFNORMALS/N
          0 for off, 1 for on. See @{"Calculate surface normals" Link "Calculate surface normals"}.

    FULLLIGHTCALCS/N
          0 for off, 1 for on. See @{"Full light calculations" Link "Full light calculations"}.

    ANTIALIASING
          Sets the anti-aliasing mode, can be `NONE', `LOW', `MEDIUM',
          `HIGH' or `VERYHIGH'. See @{"Anti-aliasing" Link "Anti-aliasing"}.

    FILEFORMAT
          Sets the current render file format. Can be `IFF-ILBM',
          `JPEG' or `TARGA'. See @{"Render file format" Link "Render file format"}.

    JPEG_QUALITY
          Sets the quality of the JPEG output. See @{"JPEG options" Link "JPEG options"}.

@{i}Returns@{ui}
     Nothing

@{i}Errors@{ui}
     rc = 0 if the operation was successful.

     rc = 10 if the operation failed for any reason, rc2 will contain a
     string describing the problem.

@{i}Example@{ui}
     The following sets the `Allow transparent object' preference off
     and sets the current render file format to be JPEG.

          PREFS_SET ALLOWTRANSOBJECT 0 FILEFORMAT "JPEG"

@{i}Known bugs@{ui}
     None.

     See @{"PREFS_GET" Link "PREFS_GET"}.


@EndNode

@Node "ARexx_RENDER" "TextureStudio.guide/ARexx_RENDER"
@Next "RENDEROPTIONS_GET"
@Prev "PREFS_SET"
@Toc "ARexx commands"

RENDER
------

@{i}Command@{ui}
     RENDER

@{i}Parameters template@{ui}
     TOBACK/S

@{i}Return template@{ui}
     None.

@{i}Description@{ui}
     Renders the current texture(s) to the HAM render screen.

@{i}Parameters@{ui}
    TOBACK/S
          If this is specified, the render screen is not brought to the
          front when rendering, it remains at the back.

@{i}Returns@{ui}
     Nothing.

@{i}Errors@{ui}
     rc = 0 if the operation was successful.

     rc = 10 if the operation failed for any reason, rc2 will contain a
     string describing the problem.

@{i}Example@{ui}
     The following renders the current texture(s) to the HAM render
     screen in the background.

          RENDER TOBACK

@{i}Known bugs@{ui}
     None.

     See @{"Render" Link "Render"}.


@EndNode

@Node "RENDEROPTIONS_GET" "TextureStudio.guide/RENDEROPTIONS_GET"
@Next "RENDEROPTIONS_SET"
@Prev "ARexx_RENDER"
@Toc "ARexx commands"

RENDEROPTIONS_GET
-----------------

@{i}Command@{ui}
     RENDEROPTIONS_GET

@{i}Parameters template@{ui}
     None.

@{i}Return template@{ui}
     WIDTH/N,HEIGHT/N,MODEID/N,TOSCREEN/N,TOFILE/N,FILE

@{i}Description@{ui}
     Gets the current render options.

@{i}Parameters@{ui}
     None.

@{i}Returns@{ui}
    WIDTH/N
          The width of the render image in pixels.

    HEIGHT/N
          The height of the render image in pixels.

    MODEID/N
          A standard Amiga mode ID describing the screen mode.

    TOSCREEN/N
          Whether the image should be rendered to the screen. 0 for
          off, 1 for on.

    TOFILE/N
          Whether the image should be rendered to a file, given by
          FILE. 0 for off, 1 for on.

    FILE
          The filename of the render file.

@{i}Errors@{ui}
     rc = 0 if the operation was successful.

     rc = 10 if the operation failed for any reason, rc2 will contain a
     string describing the problem.

@{i}Example@{ui}
     The following gets the current render options and returns them in
     a stem called `renderopts.'

          RENDEROPTIONS_GET STEM 'renderopts.'

@{i}Known bugs@{ui}
     None.

     See @{"RENDEROPTIONS_SET" Link "RENDEROPTIONS_SET"}.

     See @{"Render options" Link "Render options"}.


@EndNode

@Node "RENDEROPTIONS_SET" "TextureStudio.guide/RENDEROPTIONS_SET"
@Next "RENDERPATH_GET"
@Prev "RENDEROPTIONS_GET"
@Toc "ARexx commands"

RENDEROPTIONS_SET
-----------------

@{i}Command@{ui}
     RENDEROPTIONS_SET

@{i}Parameters template@{ui}
     WIDTH/N,HEIGHT/N,MODEID/N,TOSCREEN/N,TOFILE/N,FILE

@{i}Return template@{ui}
     None.

@{i}Description@{ui}
     Sets any of the current render options.

@{i}Parameters@{ui}
    WIDTH/N
          The width of the render image in pixels.

    HEIGHT/N
          The height of the render image in pixels.

    MODEID/N
          A standard Amiga mode ID describing the screen mode.

    TOSCREEN/N
          Whether the image should be rendered to the screen. 0 for
          off, 1 for on.

    TOFILE/N
          Whether the image should be rendered to a file, given by
          FILE. 0 for off, 1 for on.

    FILE
          The filename of the render file.

@{i}Returns@{ui}
     Nothing.

@{i}Errors@{ui}
     rc = 0 if the operation was successful.

     rc = 10 if the operation failed for any reason, rc2 will contain a
     string describing the problem.

@{i}Example@{ui}
     The following sets the render width to be 320, the height to be
     256 and the screen mode to be LowRes (mode ID = 0).

          RENDEROPTIONS_SET WIDTH 320 HEIGHT 256 MODEID 0

     The following sets the render options so that TextureStudio will
     render to a file called `Renders/Explosion.JPG' in JPEG format and
     not to render to the screen, see @{"PREFS_SET" Link "PREFS_SET"}.

          RENDEROPTIONS_SET TOSCREEN 0 TOFILE 1 FILE "Renders/Explosion.JPG"
          
          PREFS_SET FILEFORMAT "JPEG"

@{i}Known bugs@{ui}
     None.

     See @{"RENDEROPTIONS_GET" Link "RENDEROPTIONS_GET"}.

     See @{"Render options" Link "Render options"}.


@EndNode

@Node "RENDERPATH_GET" "TextureStudio.guide/RENDERPATH_GET"
@Next "RENDERSCREENPATH_GET"
@Prev "RENDEROPTIONS_SET"
@Toc "ARexx commands"

RENDERPATH_GET
--------------

@{i}Command@{ui}
     RENDERPATH_GET

@{i}Parameters template@{ui}
     None.

@{i}Return template@{ui}
     PATH

@{i}Description@{ui}
     This returns the user's current directory (path) for render files.

     This command is useful used in conjunction with FILE_JOIN, see
     @{"FILE_JOIN" Link "FILE_JOIN"}.

@{i}Parameters@{ui}
     None.

@{i}Returns@{ui}
    PATH
          The user's render path.

@{i}Errors@{ui}
     rc = 0 if the operation was successful.

     rc = 10 if the operation failed for any reason, rc2 will contain a
     string describing the problem.

@{i}Example@{ui}
     The following gets the user's render path and returns it in a
     varaible called `pathpart'

          RENDERPATH_GET VAR 'pathpart'

@{i}Known bugs@{ui}
     None.


@EndNode

@Node "RENDERSCREENPATH_GET" "TextureStudio.guide/RENDERSCREENPATH_GET"
@Next "RENDERSCREEN_CLOSE"
@Prev "RENDERPATH_GET"
@Toc "ARexx commands"

RENDERSCREENPATH_GET
--------------------

@{i}Command@{ui}
     RENDERSCREENPATH_GET

@{i}Parameters template@{ui}
     None.

@{i}Return template@{ui}
     PATH

@{i}Description@{ui}
     This returns the user's current directory (path) for render
     screens.

@{i}Parameters@{ui}
     None.

@{i}Returns@{ui}
    PATH
          The user's render screen path.

          This command is useful used in conjunction with FILE_JOIN,
          see @{"FILE_JOIN" Link "FILE_JOIN"}.

@{i}Errors@{ui}
     rc = 0 if the operation was successful.

     rc = 10 if the operation failed for any reason, rc2 will contain a
     string describing the problem.

@{i}Example@{ui}
     The following gets the user's render screen path and returns it in
     a varaible called `pathpart'

          RENDERSCREENPATH_GET VAR 'pathpart'

@{i}Known bugs@{ui}
     None.


@EndNode

@Node "RENDERSCREEN_CLOSE" "TextureStudio.guide/RENDERSCREEN_CLOSE"
@Next "RENDERSCREEN_SAVE"
@Prev "RENDERSCREENPATH_GET"
@Toc "ARexx commands"

RENDERSCREEN_CLOSE
------------------

@{i}Command@{ui}
     RENDERSCREEN_CLOSE

@{i}Parameters template@{ui}
     None.

@{i}Return template@{ui}
     None.

@{i}Description@{ui}
     Closes the current render screen. Returns an error if there is no
     render screen currently open.

     ARexx equivelent to the `Close' gadget in the Infobar window.

@{i}Parameters@{ui}
     None.

@{i}Returns@{ui}
     Nothing.

@{i}Errors@{ui}
     rc = 0 if the operation was successful.

     rc = 10 if the operation failed for any reason, rc2 will contain a
     string describing the problem.

@{i}Example@{ui}
     The following closes the current render screen.

          RENDERSCREEN_CLOSE

@{i}Known bugs@{ui}
     None.

     See @{"Infobar window" Link "Infobar window"}.


@EndNode

@Node "RENDERSCREEN_SAVE" "TextureStudio.guide/RENDERSCREEN_SAVE"
@Next "RENDERSCREEN_VIEW"
@Prev "RENDERSCREEN_CLOSE"
@Toc "ARexx commands"

RENDERSCREEN_SAVE
-----------------

@{i}Command@{ui}
     RENDERSCREEN_SAVE

@{i}Parameters template@{ui}
     FILE/A,FORCE/S

@{i}Return template@{ui}
     None.

@{i}Description@{ui}
     Saves the current render screen to the given FILE. Returns an
     error if there is no render screen currently open.

     ARexx equivelent to the `Save' gadget in the Infobar window.

@{i}Parameters@{ui}
    FILE/A
          Specifies the filename to save the HAM render screen as.

    FORCE/S
          If this is specified, files are automatically overwritten and
          no warning is given to the user.

@{i}Returns@{ui}
     Nothing.

@{i}Errors@{ui}
     rc = 0 if the operation was successful.

     rc = 10 if the operation failed for any reason, rc2 will contain a
     string describing the problem.

@{i}Example@{ui}
     The following example saves the current render screen to a file
     called `RenderScreens/Water.HAM8'. If the file already exists, it
     is overwritten.

          RENDERSCREEN_SAVE "RenderScreens/Water.HAM8" FORCE

@{i}Known bugs@{ui}
     None.

     See @{"Infobar window" Link "Infobar window"}.


@EndNode

@Node "RENDERSCREEN_VIEW" "TextureStudio.guide/RENDERSCREEN_VIEW"
@Next "REQUEST_DIR"
@Prev "RENDERSCREEN_SAVE"
@Toc "ARexx commands"

RENDERSCREEN_VIEW
-----------------

@{i}Command@{ui}
     RENDERSCREEN_VIEW

@{i}Parameters template@{ui}
     None.

@{i}Return template@{ui}
     None.

@{i}Description@{ui}
     Views the current render screen. Returns an error if there is no
     render screen currently open.

     ARexx equivelent to the `View' gadget in the Infobar window.

@{i}Parameters@{ui}
     None.

@{i}Returns@{ui}
     Nothing.

@{i}Errors@{ui}
     rc = 0 if the operation was successful.

     rc = 10 if the operation failed for any reason, rc2 will contain a
     string describing the problem.

@{i}Example@{ui}
     The following closes the current render screen.

          RENDERSCREEN_CLOSE

@{i}Known bugs@{ui}
     None.

     See @{"Infobar window" Link "Infobar window"}.


@EndNode

@Node "REQUEST_DIR" "TextureStudio.guide/REQUEST_DIR"
@Next "REQUEST_FILE"
@Prev "RENDERSCREEN_VIEW"
@Toc "ARexx commands"

REQUEST_DIR
-----------

@{i}Command@{ui}
     REQUEST_DIR

@{i}Parameters template@{ui}
     PATHPART, TITLE

@{i}Return template@{ui}
     PATHPART

@{i}Description@{ui}
     Opens a directory requester, allowing the user to choose a
     directory name.

     The other TextureStudio windows are automatically blocked when the
     requester is opened and unblocked when the requester is closed.

     In common with all TextureStudio requesters, if the user presses
     `Cancel', an error message is returned. For the script to trap
     this error, global error checking must be turned off. See
     @{"Error checking" Link "Error checking"}, for more information.

@{i}Parameters@{ui}
    PATHPART
          The default path name to put in the requester.

    TITLE
          The text for the title bar of the requester.

@{i}Returns@{ui}
    PATHPART
          The selected path from the requester.

@{i}Errors@{ui}
     rc = 0 if the operation was successful.

     rc = 10 if the operation failed for any reason or the user
     cancelled requester, rc2 will contain a string describing the
     problem.

@{i}Example@{ui}
     The following puts up a directory requester, with the results
     being put in the DIRINFO. stem:

          REQUEST_DIR STEM DIRINFO.

     The following puts up a directory requester with a default
     directory of "T:", the result being printed in a message requester:

          REQUEST_DIR PATHPART "T:" STEM DIRINFO.
          
          REQUEST_MESSAGE TEXT '"You chose '||DIRINFO.PATHPART||'"'

@{i}Known bugs@{ui}
     None.


@EndNode

@Node "REQUEST_FILE" "TextureStudio.guide/REQUEST_FILE"
@Next "REQUEST_MESSAGE"
@Prev "REQUEST_DIR"
@Toc "ARexx commands"

REQUEST_FILE
------------

@{i}Command@{ui}
     REQUEST_FILE

@{i}Parameters template@{ui}
     PATHPART, FILEPART, PATTERN, TITLE

@{i}Return template@{ui}
     FILE

@{i}Description@{ui}
     Opens a file requester, allowing the user to choose a filename.

     The other TextureStudio windows are automatically blocked when the
     requester is opened and unblocked when the requester is closed.

     In common with all TextureStudio requesters, if the user presses
     `Cancel', an error message is returned. For the script to trap
     this error, global error checking must be turned off. See
     @{"Error checking" Link "Error checking"}, for more information.

@{i}Parameters@{ui}
    PATHPART
          The default path name to put in the requester.

    FILEPART
          The default filename to put in the requester.

    PATTERN
          An AmigaDos pattern matching pattern, will only show files in
          the requester which match the given pattern. By default, all
          files are shown.

    TITLE
          The text for the title bar of the requester.

@{i}Returns@{ui}
    FILE
          The selected filename from the requester, the filename
          consists of both the FILEPART and PATHPART parts.

@{i}Errors@{ui}
     rc = 0 if the operation was successful.

     rc = 10 if the operation failed for any reason or the user
     cancelled requester, rc2 will contain a string describing the
     problem.

@{i}Example@{ui}
     The following puts up a file requester, with the results being put
     in the FILEINFO. stem:

          REQUEST_FILE STEM FILEINFO.

     The following puts up a file requester with the result being
     printed in a message requester. The default file is
     "Textures/Radar.itx":

          REQUEST_FILE PATHPART "Textures" FILEPART "Radar.itx",
             STEM FILEINFO.
          
          REQUEST_MESSAGE TEXT '"You chose '||FILEINFO.FILE||'"'

     The following will only show files with a ".itx" file extension:

          REQUEST_FILE PATTERN "#?.itx"

@{i}Known bugs@{ui}
     None.


@EndNode

@Node "REQUEST_MESSAGE" "TextureStudio.guide/REQUEST_MESSAGE"
@Next "REQUEST_MULTIFILE"
@Prev "REQUEST_FILE"
@Toc "ARexx commands"

REQUEST_MESSAGE
---------------

@{i}Command@{ui}
     REQUEST_MESSAGE

@{i}Parameters template@{ui}
     TEXT/A, BUTTONTEXT, AUTOCANCEL/S, TITLE

@{i}Return template@{ui}
     NUMBER/N

@{i}Description@{ui}
     Opens a general purpose message requester. Simple messages can be
     presented to the user for them to "OK" them. OK / Cancel
     requesters can be built with this requester, as well a complex
     multiple choice requesters.

     When designing requesters, it is worth remembering the following
     rules:

       1. The "Negative" response should be placed on the far
          right-hand button. For example, the `Cancel' button should be
          placed here.

       2. The "Positive" response should be placed on the far left-hand
          button. For example, the `OK' button should be placed here.

       3. Try to word your requesters to keep the positive and negative
          text as "OK" and "Cancel". Using options like "Go to it" and
          "Stop right here" doesn't make for a very intuitive interface.

       4. Keep the request text short. The user shouldn't have to read
          a screen full of text to find out what to do next.

       5. You should @{i}NEVER@{ui} swap the "OK" and "Cancel" buttons around.

       6. The last point is @{i}VERY@{ui} important.

     The other TextureStudio windows are automatically blocked when the
     requester is opened and unblocked when the requester is closed.

     If the AUTOCANCEL option is used and the user presses `Cancel', an
     error message is returned. For the script to trap this error,
     global error checking must be turned off. See @{"Error checking" Link "Error checking"}, for
     more information.

@{i}Parameters@{ui}
    TEXT/A
          The text to put into the requester. The text may contain
          multiple lines by including the `\n' characters in the string
          (see examples below).

    BUTTONTEXT
          The text for the buttons of the requester. The different
          buttons are seperated with a `|' character (i.e. BUTTONTEXT
          "OK|Cancel"). By default, only an "OK" button is placed in
          the requester.

    AUTOCANCEL/S
          By default REQUEST_MESSAGE simply returns the number of the
          button that the user selected. If the requester is of the OK
          / Cancel variety, specifying the AUTOCANCEL switch allows the
          requester to stop the script should the user press `Cancel'.

    TITLE
          The text for the title bar of the requester.

@{i}Returns@{ui}
    NUMBER
          The number of the selected button. If the requester has one
          button, NUMBER is set to 0. For more that one button, the
          right-most button sets NUMBER to 0, with the buttons being
          numbered from 1 upwards working left to right. For example,
          with a BUTTONTEXT of "OK|Save first|Cancel", "OK" would
          return 1, "Save first" would return 2 and "Cancel" would
          return 0.

@{i}Errors@{ui}
     rc = 0 if the operation was successful.

     rc = 10 if the operation failed for any reason, rc2 will contain a
     string describing the problem. rc will also be set to 10 if the
     AUTOCANCEL option is used and the user selects `Cancel'.

@{i}Example@{ui}
     The following puts up a message requester:

          REQUEST_MESSAGE TEXT '"Operation finished"'

     The following puts up a OK / Cancel requester, stopping the script
     if the user selects `Cancel':

          REQUEST_MESSAGE TEXT '"Continue ?"' BUTTONTEXT "OK|Cancel",
             AUTOCANCEL

     The following shows a multiple choice requester, followed by a
     requester showing which option was chosen:

          REQUEST_MESSAGE TEXT '"Choose an option..."',
             BUTTONTEXT "First|Second|Third"
          
          REQUEST_MESSAGE TEXT '"You chose option '||RESULT||'"'

     The following shows a message requester with multiple lines of
     text using the `\n' characters:

          REQUEST_MESSAGE TEXT '"Top line\nMiddle line\nBottom line"'

@{i}Known bugs@{ui}
     None.


@EndNode

@Node "REQUEST_MULTIFILE" "TextureStudio.guide/REQUEST_MULTIFILE"
@Next "SCREEN_BACK"
@Prev "REQUEST_MESSAGE"
@Toc "ARexx commands"

REQUEST_MULTIFILE
-----------------

@{i}Command@{ui}
     REQUEST_MULTIFILE

@{i}Parameters template@{ui}
     PATHPART, FILEPART, PATTERN, TITLE

@{i}Return template@{ui}
     FILES/M

@{i}Description@{ui}
     Opens a file requester, allowing the user to choose multiple
     filenames.

     The other TextureStudio windows are automatically blocked when the
     requester is opened and unblocked when the requester is closed.

     In common with all TextureStudio requesters, if the user presses
     `Cancel', an error message is returned. For the script to trap
     this error, global error checking must be turned off. See
     @{"Error checking" Link "Error checking"}, for more information.

@{i}Parameters@{ui}
    PATHPART
          The default path name to put in the requester.

    FILEPART
          The default filename to put in the requester.

    PATTERN
          An AmigaDos pattern matching pattern, will only show files in
          the requester which match the given pattern. By default, all
          files are shown.

    TITLE
          The text for the title bar of the requester.

@{i}Returns@{ui}
    FILES/M
          The selected filenames from the requester, the filenames
          consists of both the FILEPART and PATHPART parts.

@{i}Errors@{ui}
     rc = 0 if the operation was successful.

     rc = 10 if the operation failed for any reason or the user
     cancelled requester, rc2 will contain a string describing the
     problem. rc will also be set to 10 if no files are chosen.

@{i}Example@{ui}
     The following puts up a multifile requester, with the results
     being put in the MULTIFILEINFO. stem:

          REQUEST_MULTIFILE STEM MULTIFILEINFO.

     The following puts up a multifile requester, with a default path
     of "Textures" and loops through all the selected files by putting
     them in message requesters:

          REQUEST_MULTIFILE PATHPART "Textures" STEM MULTIFILENFO.
          
          do l = 0 to (MULTIFILENFO.FILES.COUNT - 1)
             REQUEST_MESSAGE TEXT '"'MULTIFILENFO.FILES.l'"',
                BUTTONTEXT '"More...|Cancel"' AUTOCANCEL
             end

@{i}Known bugs@{ui}
     If no file is chosen, the command returns a "user cancelled"
     error. This is normal.


@EndNode

@Node "SCREEN_BACK" "TextureStudio.guide/SCREEN_BACK"
@Next "SCREEN_FRONT"
@Prev "REQUEST_MULTIFILE"
@Toc "ARexx commands"

SCREEN_BACK
-----------

@{i}Command@{ui}
     SCREEN_BACK

@{i}Parameters template@{ui}
     None.

@{i}Return template@{ui}
